import Oseledets.Krieger.ZIterate

/-!
# The coding layer for Krieger's finite generator theorem: two-sided recovery (Krieger M3)

This file is the **œÉ-algebra recovery core** of Krieger's finite generator theorem. The classical
proof (Krieger 1970; Einsiedler‚ÄìLindenstrauss‚ÄìWard *Entropy in Ergodic Theory* ¬ß3) builds a finite
`Fin k`-valued partition `P` by *coding* the columns of a Rokhlin tower so that the two-sided
`P`-itinerary of a.e. point recovers its full itinerary under a fixed countable generator `Q`. The
combinatorial heart ‚Äî that `log k > h` forces the number of `N`-names to be `‚â§ k·¥∫` up to `Œµ`, so a
`Fin k` code exists ‚Äî is supplied upstream (the name-count layer M2, the Rokhlin tower M1). What
remains, and is proved here unconditionally, is the **recovery half**: *once* a candidate code `P`
has the property that every cell of `Q` is measurable with respect to the two-sided
`P`-saturation, `P` two-sidedly generates whenever `Q` does.

## The two-sided saturation and its shift-invariance

For `e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±` and a finite partition `P`, write
`twoSidedSat e P := ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)`
for the œÉ-algebra generated by the whole two-sided `P`-itinerary
(`Oseledets.Krieger.IsGeneratingTwoSided e P` is exactly `twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±`). The single
structural fact that drives everything is **shift-invariance**: pulling `twoSidedSat e P` back by
any iterate `e·µê` lands inside `twoSidedSat e P` again, because reindexing the `‚Ñ§`-supremum
`n ‚Ü¶ n + m` is a bijection of `‚Ñ§` (`comap_twoSidedSat_le`). This is precisely where two-sidedness
(`‚®Ü` over `‚Ñ§`, not `‚Ñï`) is load-bearing: a forward `‚Ñï`-supremum is *not* shift-invariant under the
backward iterate `e‚Åª¬π`.

Shift-invariance immediately gives the **recovery / refinement-monotonicity** lemma: if every cell
of `Q` is `twoSidedSat e P`-measurable (`œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`), then `Q`'s entire two-sided
saturation sits inside `P`'s (`twoSidedSat_mono_of_le`), so a generator `Q` lifts to a generator
`P` (`IsGeneratingTwoSided.of_le`). This is the two-sided analogue of
`Oseledets.Entropy.IsGenerating.mono_refine`.

## The coding interface consumed by the headline

The upstream coding construction is exposed to the headline through the predicate
`CodesTwoSided e Q P`, which packages exactly the recovery hypothesis `œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`. The
headline (`Oseledets.Krieger.krieger_finite_generator`) takes the *existence* of a `Fin k`-valued
`P` with `CodesTwoSided e Q P` (the conclusion of the M1+M2 combinatorics) and concludes
`IsGeneratingTwoSided e P` via `CodesTwoSided.isGeneratingTwoSided`.

## Main definitions

* `Oseledets.Krieger.twoSidedSat`: the two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra `‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)`.
* `Oseledets.Krieger.CodesTwoSided`: `P`'s two-sided itinerary recovers each cell of `Q`.

## Main results

* `Oseledets.Krieger.comap_twoSidedSat_le`: shift-invariance of the two-sided saturation.
* `Oseledets.Krieger.twoSidedSat_mono_of_le`: œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P ‚üπ twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§
  twoSidedSat e P.
* `Oseledets.Krieger.IsGeneratingTwoSided.of_le`: recovery lifts a two-sided generator.
* `Oseledets.Krieger.CodesTwoSided.isGeneratingTwoSided`: a code of a two-sided generator is a
  two-sided generator.

## References

* Wolfgang Krieger, *On entropy and generators of measure-preserving transformations*,
  Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. **149** (1970), 453‚Äì464.
* Manfred Einsiedler, Elon Lindenstrauss and Thomas Ward, *Entropy in Ergodic Theory and
  Homogeneous Dynamics* (book in progress), ¬ß3 (the Krieger generator theorem).
* Eli Glasner, *Ergodic Theory via Joinings*, Math. Surveys Monogr. **101**, AMS (2003) ‚Äî Krieger
  chapter.
* Tomasz Downarowicz, *Entropy in Dynamical Systems*, Cambridge (2011).
-/

open MeasureTheory Function MeasurableSpace

namespace Oseledets.Krieger

variable {Œ± : Type*} {Œπ Œ∫ : Type*} [mŒ± : MeasurableSpace Œ±] [Fintype Œπ] [Fintype Œ∫]
  {Œº : Measure Œ±}

open Oseledets.Entropy

/-- The **two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra** of a finite partition `P` under the automorphism `e`:
the supremum, over all integer iterates `e‚Åø` (`n : ‚Ñ§`), of the pulled-back generating œÉ-algebra
`œÉ(P)`. A set is `twoSidedSat e P`-measurable exactly when it is determined by the (two-sided)
`P`-itinerary `n ‚Ü¶ (the cell of P containing e‚Åø x)`. By definition, `P` two-sidedly generates
`(Œ±, e, Œº)` iff `twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±`. Marked `@[reducible]` (its value is a `MeasurableSpace`, a
class type) so it unfolds for instance resolution and definitional rewriting, mirroring
`Oseledets.Entropy.generatedSigmaAlgebra`. -/
@[reducible]
noncomputable def twoSidedSat (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) : MeasurableSpace Œ± :=
  ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e n) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P)

@[simp]
lemma twoSidedSat_def (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) :
    twoSidedSat e P = ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e n) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P) :=
  rfl

lemma isGeneratingTwoSided_iff (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) :
    IsGeneratingTwoSided e P ‚Üî twoSidedSat e P = mŒ± := Iff.rfl

/-- **Shift-invariance of the two-sided saturation.** Pulling the two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra
`twoSidedSat e P` back by any iterate `e·µê` lands inside it again:
`comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`.

A generator of `comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P)` is `e·µê‚Åª¬π` of a generator of one of the `‚Ñ§`-terms,
namely `comap (e·µê) (comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)) = comap (e‚Åø ‚àò e·µê) œÉ(P) = comap (e^{n+m}) œÉ(P)` (using
`ziter_add`), which is the `(n + m)`-th term of the same `‚Ñ§`-supremum. This is *exactly* where the
two-sided (`‚Ñ§`) indexing is essential: the reindexing `n ‚Ü¶ n + m` is a bijection of `‚Ñ§`, so no
terms are lost ‚Äî a forward (`‚Ñï`) supremum would lose terms under a backward shift. -/
theorem comap_twoSidedSat_le (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) (m : ‚Ñ§) :
    MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e m) (twoSidedSat e P) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P := by
  rw [twoSidedSat_def, MeasurableSpace.comap_iSup]
  refine iSup_le fun n => ?_
  rw [MeasurableSpace.comap_comp, ‚Üê ziter_add]
  exact le_iSup (fun k : ‚Ñ§ => MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e k) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P)) (n + m)

/-- **Recovery / refinement monotonicity for two-sided generation.** If every cell of `Q` is
measurable with respect to the two-sided `P`-saturation (`œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P` ‚Äî the
`P`-itinerary recovers each `Q`-cell), then the *entire* two-sided saturation of `Q` sits inside
that of `P`:
`twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`.

Each `‚Ñ§`-term `comap (e·µê) œÉ(Q)` of `twoSidedSat e Q` is bounded, by `comap`-monotonicity in the
hypothesis, by `comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P)`, which is `‚â§ twoSidedSat e P` by shift-invariance
(`comap_twoSidedSat_le`). Taking the supremum over `m` gives the claim. -/
theorem twoSidedSat_mono_of_le (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) (Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫)
    (hrec : generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P) :
    twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P := by
  rw [twoSidedSat_def (P := Q)]
  refine iSup_le fun m => ?_
  exact le_trans (MeasurableSpace.comap_mono hrec) (comap_twoSidedSat_le e P m)

/-- **Recovery lifts a two-sided generator.** If `Q` two-sidedly generates `(Œ±, e, Œº)` and the
two-sided `P`-itinerary recovers each cell of `Q` (`œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`), then `P` two-sidedly
generates as well.

The ambient œÉ-algebra always dominates `twoSidedSat e P` (each cell of `P` is measurable, so
`œÉ(P) ‚â§ mŒ±`, hence every term `comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P) ‚â§ mŒ±`). For the reverse inclusion,
`mŒ± = twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P` by `Q`'s generation and `twoSidedSat_mono_of_le`;
antisymmetry pins `twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±`. This is the two-sided analogue of
`Oseledets.Entropy.IsGenerating.mono_refine`. -/
theorem IsGeneratingTwoSided.of_le {e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±} {P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ}
    {Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫} (hQ : IsGeneratingTwoSided e Q)
    (hrec : generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P) :
    IsGeneratingTwoSided e P := by
  rw [isGeneratingTwoSided_iff]
  -- `twoSidedSat e P ‚â§ mŒ±`: each cell of `P` is measurable.
  have hP_le : generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P ‚â§ mŒ± := by
    refine MeasurableSpace.generateFrom_le ?_
    rintro s ‚ü®i, rfl‚ü©
    exact P.measurable i
  have hsat_le : twoSidedSat e P ‚â§ mŒ± := by
    rw [twoSidedSat_def]
    refine iSup_le fun n => ?_
    exact le_trans (MeasurableSpace.comap_mono hP_le) (measurable_ziter e n).comap_le
  -- `mŒ± = twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`.
  refine le_antisymm hsat_le ?_
  calc mŒ± = twoSidedSat e Q := ((isGeneratingTwoSided_iff e Q).mp hQ).symm
    _ ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P := twoSidedSat_mono_of_le e P Q hrec

/-- **The coding predicate.** A finite `Fin k`-valued (or `Œπ`-valued) partition `P` *codes* a
partition `Q` two-sidedly under `e` when the two-sided `P`-itinerary recovers every cell of `Q`:
each cell of `Q` is measurable with respect to `twoSidedSat e P`.

This is the exact conclusion of the Krieger coding construction (Rokhlin tower + name count): the
column-coding partition `P` is built so that, off a null set, the two-sided `P`-itinerary of a
point determines its `Q`-itinerary, hence in particular which `Q`-cell it lies in. The headline
consumes the *existence* of such a `P` and turns it into a generator via
`CodesTwoSided.isGeneratingTwoSided`. -/
def CodesTwoSided (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) : Prop :=
  generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº Q ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P

/-- A code of a two-sided generator is itself a two-sided generator ‚Äî the headline reduction.
Immediate from `IsGeneratingTwoSided.of_le` and the definition of `CodesTwoSided`. -/
theorem CodesTwoSided.isGeneratingTwoSided {e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±} {Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫}
    {P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ} (hQ : IsGeneratingTwoSided e Q) (hP : CodesTwoSided e Q P) :
    IsGeneratingTwoSided e P :=
  IsGeneratingTwoSided.of_le hQ hP

/-- **Reflexivity of coding.** Every partition codes itself two-sidedly: its own static œÉ-algebra
`œÉ(Q)` is the `n = 0` term `comap (e‚Å∞) œÉ(Q) = comap id œÉ(Q) = œÉ(Q)` of its two-sided saturation,
hence `œÉ(Q) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e Q`. (Sanity check: a two-sided generator codes itself, recovering
`IsGeneratingTwoSided e Q` from itself.) -/
theorem codesTwoSided_self (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫) : CodesTwoSided e Q Q := by
  rw [CodesTwoSided, twoSidedSat_def]
  refine le_trans (le_of_eq ?_) (le_iSup _ (0 : ‚Ñ§))
  rw [ziter_zero, MeasurableSpace.comap_id]

end Oseledets.Krieger
